  "nursesNote": "Intellectual disability involves deficits in intellectual functioning and adaptive (everyday) skills that begin in childhood and range from mild to profound. The nurse communicates at the person's developmental level using simple, concrete, one-step instructions and demonstrations, and promotes maximum independence by encouraging the activities of daily living the person can do rather than over-helping. Tasks are broken into small steps with repetition and praise. A consistent routine reduces confusion, the environment is adapted for safety with supervision as needed, and the person is treated with age-appropriate dignity (not talked to as a young child if they are an adult). The nurse positively reinforces effort and success and works with caregivers, who know the patient best, to plan care.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Communicate at the patient's developmental level",
    "Promote independence in activities of daily living",
    "Break tasks into small steps with praise",
    "Keep a consistent routine and adapt the environment for safety",
    "Treat the patient with age-appropriate respect and involve caregivers"
  ],
